Improve parsing of counter/counters CSS content functions (#705)Instead of exploding the string based on the argument delimeter (,)nparse the string using a regex that pulls the arguments into anmatches array ($args). This allows for the presence of a commanin the joining string argument of the counters() function.nnThe output from the counters() function was also updated. Firstnthe joining string is now only used between the counter instancesnwhere previously it was also appended to the end of the output.nSecond, elements that reset the counter but do not actuallynincrement it are skipped. This matches the output generated bynstandards-compliant browsers.n

Improve determination of element relevance to CSS counters (#705)The previous commit was deficient in determining when an elementnincremented the counter being parsed by the counters() function.nIn the previous commit elements with a value less than 1 werenexcluded from the output string. However, since elements can be setnto decrement counters we need to allow values less than 1. The codennow checks to see if the current element resets the counter beingnprocessed.n

Better placement of absolutely-positioned elements (#721)When an element is positioned absolutely without specifyingnthe top/right/bottom/left properties (or when thosenproperties are set to auto) it should now be placed on thenpage according to where it would fall in the normal documentnflow. The positioning code also now searches for a block-levelnparent element rather than assume that the containing elementnis a block-level element.n
Simplified last commit

Improve compressed CSS parsing of at-rule blocks (#614,#699)The previous regex that identified at-rule blocks was unable tonhandle compressed CSS. Specifically, a missing space between thenrule name and the declaration block delimeter } would cause thenregex to miss the rule. This slight modification seems to addressnthe issue.n

Improve counter handling (fixes #440, #710)If an element that increments a counter was rendered but pushednto the next page because of lack of space the counter would benincremented a second time. Now when splitting an element dompdfnwill decrement counters that were incremented.nnAlso, nested counters would break depending on where the pagingntook place. Because dompdf reset counters as it climbed up thenelement tree higher levels of nested counters were being reset.nNow dompdf saves the current value of any counters on an elementnthat is split. When that element is re-rendered on the next pagenthe counter value is set according to the saved value.nnAdditional modifications improve improve handling of the use casenoutlined in #705.n

Encode non-display text streams to UTF16In order for CPDF to correctly support the full Unicode character set in metadata fields we need to encode to UTF16 with BOM. Remove text nodes from the head element when loading the documentThe head element should only contain metadata content. Also, Dompdf may have difficulties when text content is contained inside the head element (e.g. no block-level parent found errors). As such we'll add the head element to the list of elements where text node children are removed.n

Only use the style default if not set or inheritance has not been appliedBefore this change we would use the default value if no computed value were present or if the specified property value was inherit. However, if the computed value has been set we should use it. Except when its value is inherit in which case inheritance has not yet been applied.nnThis is a fallback, since in the normal Dompdf process flow inheritance will have been applied prior to accessing a style value via the getter.n

Render table background inside table bordersThis commit changes the rendering of a table cell's background when border-collapse is set to collapse.nnBefore this commit Dompdf would render the background of a table cell based on the full cell width, disregarding any border. For collapsed cells Dompdf also preferentially renders the right and top border of a cell, only rendering the bottom and left if the cell is at the end of a row or column. This means the border of adjacent cells is rendered around only one of the cells.nnBecause of the stacking order of objects in the PDF, the border of a row-spanned cell was being covered by cells on following rows. This change modifies the background position and sizing to account for borders.nnAddresses #1033n

do not allow failure on php 7.3

Consider adjecent table cells border width when rendering backgroundBefore this commit Dompdf would only consider the rendered borders of the cell being rendered. This was producing undesireable results when the adjacent cell had a larger border than the current cell, and when it was that cell's border being rendered. In that situation the current cell's background would render into the space occupied by the border.nnThis update considers the width of all borders rendered around the cell being rendered.nnAddresses #1033n
